Introduction to Placement and Problem Area

Placement Description: Machine Leaning and Data Visualization¶

In the area of Big Data analysis, powerful tools include machine learning and data visualization. Data visualization offers clear, interactive representations of complicated information, while machine learning enables the automatic extraction of patterns and insights from vast datasets. Together, they improve comprehension and judgment. Hastie et al. (2009) claim that machine learning algorithms enable the creation of prediction models, while Tufte (2001) underlines the significance of correct data visualization in information dissemination.

According to World Health Organization (2022), cardiovascular diseases (CVDs) are the leading cause of death globally, taking an estimated 17.9 million lives each year. CVDs are a group of disorders of the heart and blood vessels and include coronary heart disease, cerebrovascular disease, rheumatic heart disease and other conditions. More than four out of five CVD deaths are due to heart attacks and strokes, and one third of these deaths occur prematurely in people under 70 years of age (World Heath Organization, 2022).

Heart disease is the leading cause of death for men, women, and people of most racial and ethnic groups in the United States, and it has been recorded by the Centre for Disease Control and Prevention (CDCP) that one person dies every 34 seconds in the United States from heart disease (Centre for Diseases Control and Prevention, 2022).

The healthcare sector has long been an early adopter of technological advances. These days, machine learning, a subset of artificial intelligence, plays a key role in many health innovations, including the development of new medical procedures, the handling of patient records and the treatment of chronic diseases (Thomas, 2022).

Objectives of the Placement

To describe the dataset with descriptive analysis and visualizations.

To investigate the effect of various lifestyle indicators, environmental factors and clinical characteristics on the risk of heart diseases.

To build machine learning models that predicts the heart diseases status of an individual based on their other clinical and demographics characteristics.

About the Data Set

The dataset to be used for this project is a heart disease dataset obtained from a free and open-source data website. Originally, the dataset comes from the CDC and is a major part of the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS), which conducts annual telephone surveys to gather data on the health status of U.S residents. As the CDC describes: Established in 1984 with 15 states, BRFSS bow collects data in all 50 states as well as district od Columbia and three U.S territories. BRFSS completes more than 400,000 adult interviews each year, making it the largest continuously conducted health survey system in the world. The most recent dataset (as of February 15, 2020) incudes data from 20202. It consists of 401, 958 rows and 279 columns. The vast majority of the columns are questions asked from respondents about their health status, such as smoking status, difficulty in walking or climbing stairs, and others, but the 18 most relevant questions or variables that most directly or indirectly influence he risk of heart diseases was filtered out from the enormous dataset. Therefore, the heart diseases data to be used in the study consist of 18 columns and 319,795 observations, and be accessed at https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/kamilpytlak/personal-key-indicators-of-heart-disease

Machine Learning Algorithm to be used

In this placement, various machine learning classification algorithms was used to model and make predictions on the dataset. They include:

Logistics Regression

Random Forest Classifier

Decision Tree Classifier and

Nave Bayes Classifier.

Steps Involved¶

Firstly, the data set was loaded into Python, on Jupyter notebook, and the dataset undergo preprocessing at first stage, where the data was studied, cleaned and preprocessed to ensure its quality and suitability for machine learning algorithms. This involves handling missing values, removing outliers, and normalizing or standardizing features.

The second stage is the Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) stage where the dataset was explored using lots of visualizations including pie chart, bar plots, histograms, boxplots and many more. This helps us to understand how patients clinical, social and lifestyle influences each other.

The last steps and stage of the project is the building of the machine learning models. This process involves scaling the dataset, splitting the data sets into training and testing sets, thereby, training the training set and using the model trained to predict and test the testing set.

SUMMARY OF FINDINGS AND CONCLUSIONS

  1. Majority (91.4% ) of the recorded patients in this Heart Diseases Dataset are diagnosed to have no heart diseases, where 8.1% (27,373 patients) have heart diseases. This tells that the data is not balance.

  2. From the correlation test in the Data Exploratory part of this project, it can be seen that all the variables (BMI, Physical Health ratings, Mental Health rating and Sleep Time) have a very weak correlations among each other, where sleep time was estimated to have a very weak and negative correlation of 0.052, 0.061 and 0.0119 with BMI, Physical Health, and Mentral Health respectively.

  3. Also, Female dominates the population of this study than Male, with a percentage of 52.5% compare to 47.5% for Male. Where, just 6.8% are smokers and as high as 93.2% are not. Moreso, 13.9% of the population has difficulty in walking where 86.1% do not.

  4. Further more, observations in the datsdet are dominated with those between the age range of 60-64years and 65-69years constituing approximtely 11% each to the distribution, where the age group with the least frquency are those between 25-29.

  5. Moreso, the data set was processed and then splited by 80:20 where 80% (255836 rows) of the datset where used to train five classification algorithmns seperately where 20% was uses as testing set, to test the trained model. The results showed that both Logistics Regression outperforms all the other model with an accuracy score of 91.3% and a model score of 0.916, where Random Forest Classifier has an accuracy percent of 90.4% with a model score of 0.997 . Also, Decicion Tree Classifier still manage to have an accuracy percent of 86.2% and Niave bayes has 84.3%.
